President Biden on Thursday responded to the hecklers during his prime-time speech in Philadelphia, saying that a democracy allows them to protest.



“They’re entitled to be outrageous. This is a democracy,” the president said in the middle of his remarks.



Protesters yelled from outside of the Independence National Historical Park: “Let’s go, Brandon” and “F Joe Biden.” The phrase “Let’s Go Brandon” quickly became a political slogan adopted former President Trump’s base after a TV commentator mistakenly interpreted a crowd chanting of “f--- Joe Biden” as “Let’s Go Brandon,” in support of NASCAR driver Brandon Brown.



Biden’s speech on Thursday was&nbsp;centered around warning&nbsp;that Trump and Republicans aligned with him are threats to the country. It was framed beforehand as remarks about “the soul of the nation.”&nbsp;



Biden also snapped back at those yelling during his remarks, saying, “good manners is nothing they’ve ever suffered from,”&nbsp;according to&nbsp;Reuters White House reporter Jeff Mason.&nbsp;



The president emphasized in his remarks the danger of MAGA-aligned Republicans, arguing that they cast doubt on election results, spread conspiracy theories, attack law enforcement, do not respect the Constitution and have blind loyalty for Trump.&nbsp;



Biden has had other interruptions during speeches throughout his presidency. In July, the president&nbsp;was interrupted by Manuel Oliver, the father of mass shooting victim Joaquin Oliver, during an event at the White House.



Biden responded, “let him talk, let him talk” when Oliver appeared to suggest that the bipartisan gun control bill did not go far enough.

outlineJsontext:
{
    "text": "Reach, yes, but staying power?",
    "created": "Fri, 02 Sep 2022 02:29:59 GMT",
    "type": "outline",
    "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/01/022959.html?title=reachYesButStayingPower",
    "subs": [
        {
            "text": "Made up of humans, flawed in its own ways, the Democratic Party has often seemed afraid, during the years since Ronald Reagan seemed to charm the country's right wingers into a passionate stance that has not ever quite gone away. And it has been injected with new life repeatedly by people like Gingrich, Bannon, Miller, and Trump. But tonight the President get serious in a way that members of his party seldom seem to do.",
            "created": "Fri, 02 Sep 2022 02:32:25 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/01/022959.html?title=reachYesButStayingPower#a023225",
            "subs": [
                {
                    "text": "“There’s no question that the Republican Party today is dominated, driven and intimidated by Donald Trump and the MAGA Republicans. And that is a threat to this country.”",
                    "created": "Fri, 02 Sep 2022 02:35:08 GMT",
                    "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/01/022959.html?title=reachYesButStayingPower#a023508"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "News evaporates in the United States, and bold statements too. But if the President's voice can have not just reach but staying power, then this will have been an important moment for the country, for the election coming up, and beyond.",
            "created": "Fri, 02 Sep 2022 02:35:31 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/01/022959.html?title=reachYesButStayingPower#a023531"
        },
        {
            "text": "Having allies helps with reach, for we can all amplify and extend the message and its implications, if we care to stir ourselves. Staying power is touchier, since organizations like Fox were probably trying to drown out the speech before it even commenced. Amplify and extend, amplify and extend. Lather, rinse, repeat. Repeat. Repeat.",
            "created": "Fri, 02 Sep 2022 02:36:51 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/01/022959.html?title=reachYesButStayingPower#a023651"
        }
    ]
}
